            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Alina Hayes is a product of two Bay Area worlds. Raised in suburban San Jose by her Korean immigrant mother, a meticulous seamstress, and her pragmatic Caucasian father, an engineer, she learned to appreciate both artistry and the bottom line. Her childhood was a blend of colorful fabric scraps and structured logic, a duality that defined her path. While her friends were at the mall, Alina was learning to identify different weaves and stitch patterns from her mother, who instilled in her a deep respect for craftsmanship.\n\nRejecting the tech-centric path of her hometown, Alina moved to the city to attend San Francisco State University. She thrived in the energy of the urban campus, earning her degree in Fashion Merchandising and landing a coveted internship at a major downtown department store. Her keen eye and surprising grasp of analytics saw her rise quickly from an assistant to a buyer. A key turning point came during a major corporate restructuring five years ago; while others were laid off, Alina\u2019s ability to forecast trends while ruthlessly managing budgets saved her department, solidifying her reputation and securing her promotion to Senior Buyer.\n\nNow 36, Alina lives in a thoughtfully decorated one-bedroom apartment in the Inner Richmond. Her daily routine is a ritual: a morning ride on the 38 Geary Express, podcast playing, mentally preparing for a day of vendor negotiations and spreadsheet analysis. Evenings are for decompressing with a run in Golden Gate Park or exploring the authentic eateries on Clement Street, a comforting nod to her heritage. After a recent, amicable split with a long-term partner who wanted to move to the suburbs, she has poured her energy back into her work and a close circle of friends.\n\nAlina\u2019s connection to San Francisco is core to her identity\u2014she loves its blend of grit and gloss. While she is proud of her corporate success, her dream is to launch her own sustainable, direct-to-consumer fashion line. She spends her weekends sketching designs and researching ethical fabric sourcing, aspiring to build something that honors her mother\u2019s craft while reflecting her own modern, strategic vision."
